Montenegro, located on the Adriatic Sea in Southeastern Europe, generally has a Mediterranean climate along the coast and a more continental climate in the interior regions.

Along the coast, summers are typically hot and dry, with temperatures often reaching the 80s and 90s Fahrenheit (around 27-37°C). Winters are mild and wet, with temperatures usually ranging from the 40s to 50s Fahrenheit (around 4-15°C). 

Inland areas, such as the mountainous regions, experience colder winters with snowfall, and summers are cooler compared to the coastal areas.

Overall, Montenegro offers a diverse climate due to its varied topography, ranging from coastal plains to rugged mountains, so weather conditions can vary depending on the specific location within the country. It's always a good idea to check the local weather forecast for the most accurate information before planning your visit.